==English==
{{Wikipedia|Clockwise and counterclockwise}}
===Pronunciation===
*[[w:Received Pronunciation|RP]] in {{IPA|/ˌæntɪˈklɒkwaɪz/}}, /<tt>%{ntI"klQkwaIz</tt>/
*(''US''): ăn'tēkläkʹwīz, /ˌæntiˈklɑkwaɪz/, /<tt>%{nti"klAkwaIz</tt>/ ''or'' ăn'tīkläkʹwīz, /ˌæntaɪˈklɑkwaɪz/, /<tt>%{ntaI"klAkwaIz</tt>/
<!--Note: while this is a word in British usage but not American, the word features in US dictionaries and therefore has an American pronunciation too (imagine an American reading a British English text aloud, for example).  The US pronunciation therefore belongs here. -->

===Adjective===
'''anticlockwise''' (''British'')

#{{not comparable}} Of movement, in a circular fashion so as to be moving to the left at the top of the circle and to the right at the bottom, in the opposite direction to the way the [[hand]]s of an [[analogue]] clock move.

====Synonyms====
*[[counterclockwise]] ''or'' [[counter-clockwise]] (''US''), [[laevorotatory]] (''UK'') ''or'' [[levorotatory]] (''US'') (''chemistry''), [[positive]] (''geometry'')

====Antonyms====
*[[clockwise]]

===Adverb===
'''anticlockwise''' (''British'')
#{{not comparable}} In an anticlockwise fashion.

====Synonyms====
*[[counterclockwise]] ''or'' [[counter-clockwise]] (''US''), [[widdershins]] ''or'' [[withershins]] (''particularly on a sundial'')

====Antonyms====
*[[clockwise]]

